#: ../../../reference/testing.rst:4
msgid "Testing guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:2
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:4
msgid ""
"Until the 1.15 release, NumPy used the `nose`_ testing framework, it now "
"uses the `pytest`_ framework. The older framework is still maintained in "
"order to support downstream projects that use the old numpy framework, but "
"all tests for NumPy should use pytest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:9
msgid ""
"Our goal is that every module and package in NumPy should have a thorough "
"set of unit tests. These tests should exercise the full functionality of a "
"given routine as well as its robustness to erroneous or unexpected input "
"arguments. Well-designed tests with good coverage make an enormous "
"difference to the ease of refactoring. Whenever a new bug is found in a "
"routine, you should write a new test for that specific case and add it to "
"the test suite to prevent that bug from creeping back in unnoticed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:21
msgid ""
"SciPy uses the testing framework from :mod:`numpy.testing`, so all of the "
"NumPy examples shown below are also applicable to SciPy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:25
msgid "Testing NumPy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:27
msgid ""
"NumPy can be tested in a number of ways, choose any way you feel comfortable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:30
msgid "Running tests from inside Python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:32
msgid ""
"You can test an installed NumPy by `numpy.test`, for example, To run NumPy's "
"full test suite, use the following::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:35
msgid ""
">>> import numpy\n"
">>> numpy.test(label='slow')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:38
msgid ""
"The test method may take two or more arguments; the first ``label`` is a "
"string specifying what should be tested and the second ``verbose`` is an "
"integer giving the level of output verbosity. See the docstring `numpy.test` "
"for details. The default value for ``label`` is 'fast' - which will run the "
"standard tests.  The string 'full' will run the full battery of tests, "
"including those identified as being slow to run. If ``verbose`` is 1 or "
"less, the tests will just show information messages about the tests that are "
"run; but if it is greater than 1, then the tests will also provide warnings "
"on missing tests. So if you want to run every test and get messages about "
"which modules don't have tests::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:50
msgid ">>> numpy.test(label='full', verbose=2)  # or numpy.test('full', 2)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:52
msgid ""
"Finally, if you are only interested in testing a subset of NumPy, for "
"example, the ``_core`` module, use the following::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:55
msgid ">>> numpy._core.test()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:58
msgid "Running tests from the command line"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:60
msgid ""
"If you want to build NumPy in order to work on NumPy itself, use the :ref:"
"`spin utility <spin_tool>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:63
msgid "To run NumPy's full test suite::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:65
msgid "$ spin test -m full"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:67
msgid "Testing a subset of NumPy::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:69
msgid "$ spin test -t numpy/_core/tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:71
msgid "For detailed info on testing, see :ref:`testing-builds`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:74
msgid "Running tests in multiple threads"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:76
msgid ""
"To help with stress testing NumPy for thread safety, the test suite can be "
"run under `pytest-run-parallel`_. To install ``pytest-run-parallel``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:79
msgid "$ pip install pytest-run-parallel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:81
msgid "To run the test suite in multiple threads::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:83
msgid ""
"$ spin test -p auto # have pytest-run-parallel detect the number of "
"available cores\n"
"$ spin test -p 4 # run each test under 4 threads\n"
"$ spin test -p auto -- --skip-thread-unsafe=true # run ONLY tests that are "
"thread-safe"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:87
msgid ""
"When you write new tests, it is worth testing to make sure they do not fail "
"under ``pytest-run-parallel``, since the CI jobs make use of it. Some tips "
"on how to write thread-safe tests can be found `here <#writing-thread-safe-"
"tests>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:93
msgid ""
"Ideally you should run ``pytest-run-parallel`` using a `free-threaded build "
"of Python <https://docs.python.org/3/howto/free-threading-python.html>`_ "
"that is 3.14 or higher. If you decide to use a version of Python that is not "
"free-threaded, you will need to set the environment variables "
"``PYTHON_CONTEXT_AWARE_WARNINGS`` and ``PYTHON_THREAD_INHERIT_CONTEXT`` to 1."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:100
msgid "Running doctests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:102
msgid ""
"NumPy documentation contains code examples, \"doctests\". To check that the "
"examples are correct, install the ``scipy-doctest`` package::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:105
msgid "$ pip install scipy-doctest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:107
msgid "and run one of::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:109
msgid ""
"$ spin check-docs -v\n"
"$ spin check-docs numpy/linalg\n"
"$ spin check-docs -- -k 'det and not slogdet'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:113
msgid "Note that the doctests are not run when you use ``spin test``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:117
msgid "Other methods of running tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:119
msgid "Run tests using your favourite IDE such as `vscode`_ or `pycharm`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:122
msgid "Writing your own tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:124
msgid ""
"If you are writing code that you'd like to become part of NumPy, please "
"write the tests as you develop your code. Every Python module, extension "
"module, or subpackage in the NumPy package directory should have a "
"corresponding ``test_<name>.py`` file. Pytest examines these files for test "
"methods (named ``test*``) and test classes (named ``Test*``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:131
msgid ""
"Suppose you have a NumPy module ``numpy/xxx/yyy.py`` containing a function "
"``zzz()``.  To test this function you would create a test module called "
"``test_yyy.py``.  If you only need to test one aspect of ``zzz``, you can "
"simply add a test function::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:136
msgid ""
"def test_zzz():\n"
"    assert zzz() == 'Hello from zzz'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:139
msgid ""
"More often, we need to group a number of tests together, so we create a test "
"class::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:142
msgid ""
"# import xxx symbols\n"
"from numpy.xxx.yyy import zzz\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"class TestZzz:\n"
"    def test_simple(self):\n"
"        assert zzz() == 'Hello from zzz'\n"
"\n"
"    def test_invalid_parameter(self):\n"
"        with pytest.raises(ValueError, match='.*some matching regex.*'):\n"
"            ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:154
msgid ""
"Within these test methods, the ``assert`` statement or a specialized "
"assertion function is used to test whether a certain assumption is valid. If "
"the assertion fails, the test fails. Common assertion functions include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:158
msgid ""
":func:`numpy.testing.assert_equal` for testing exact elementwise equality "
"between a result array and a reference,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:160
msgid ""
":func:`numpy.testing.assert_allclose` for testing near elementwise equality "
"between a result array and a reference (i.e. with specified relative and "
"absolute tolerances), and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:163
msgid ""
":func:`numpy.testing.assert_array_less` for testing (strict) elementwise "
"ordering between a result array and a reference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:166
msgid ""
"By default, these assertion functions only compare the numerical values in "
"the arrays. Consider using the ``strict=True`` option to check the array "
"dtype and shape, too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:170
msgid ""
"When you need custom assertions, use the Python ``assert`` statement. Note "
"that ``pytest`` internally rewrites ``assert`` statements to give "
"informative output when it fails, so it should be preferred over the legacy "
"variant ``numpy.testing.assert_``. Whereas plain ``assert`` statements are "
"ignored when running Python in optimized mode with ``-O``, this is not an "
"issue when running tests with pytest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:177
msgid ""
"Similarly, the pytest functions :func:`pytest.raises` and :func:`pytest."
"warns` should be preferred over their legacy counterparts :func:`numpy."
"testing.assert_raises` and :func:`numpy.testing.assert_warns`, which are "
"more broadly used. These versions also accept a ``match`` parameter, which "
"should always be used to precisely target the intended warning or error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:184
msgid ""
"Note that ``test_`` functions or methods should not have a docstring, "
"because that makes it hard to identify the test from the output of running "
"the test suite with ``verbose=2`` (or similar verbosity setting).  Use plain "
"comments (``#``) to describe the intent of the test and help the unfamiliar "
"reader to interpret the code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:190
msgid ""
"Also, since much of NumPy is legacy code that was originally written without "
"unit tests, there are still several modules that don't have tests yet. "
"Please feel free to choose one of these modules and develop tests for it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:196
msgid "Using C code in tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:198
msgid ""
"NumPy exposes a rich :ref:`C-API<c-api>` . These are tested using c-"
"extension modules written \"as-if\" they know nothing about the internals of "
"NumPy, rather using the official C-API interfaces only. Examples of such "
"modules are tests for a user-defined ``rational`` dtype in "
"``_rational_tests`` or the ufunc machinery tests in ``_umath_tests`` which "
"are part of the binary distribution. Starting from version 1.21, you can "
"also write snippets of C code in tests that will be compiled locally into c-"
"extension modules and loaded into python."
msgstr ""

