#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:211
msgid "Labeling tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:213
msgid ""
"Unlabeled tests like the ones above are run in the default ``numpy.test()`` "
"run.  If you want to label your test as slow - and therefore reserved for a "
"full ``numpy.test(label='full')`` run, you can label it with ``pytest.mark."
"slow``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:218
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.slow\n"
"def test_big(self):\n"
"    print('Big, slow test')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:224
msgid "Similarly for methods::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:226
msgid ""
"class test_zzz:\n"
"    @pytest.mark.slow\n"
"    def test_simple(self):\n"
"        assert_(zzz() == 'Hello from zzz')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:232
msgid "Setup and teardown methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:234
msgid ""
"NumPy originally used xunit setup and teardown, a feature of `pytest`. We "
"now encourage the usage of setup and teardown methods that are called "
"explicitly by the tests that need them::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:238
msgid ""
"class TestMe:\n"
"    def setup(self):\n"
"        print('doing setup')\n"
"        return 1\n"
"\n"
"    def teardown(self):\n"
"        print('doing teardown')\n"
"\n"
"    def test_xyz(self):\n"
"        x = self.setup()\n"
"        assert x == 1\n"
"        self.teardown()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:251
msgid ""
"This approach is thread-safe, ensuring tests can run under ``pytest-run-"
"parallel``. Using pytest setup fixtures (such as xunit setup methods) is "
"generally not thread-safe and will likely cause thread-safety test failures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:255
msgid ""
"``pytest`` supports more general fixture at various scopes which may be used "
"automatically via special arguments. For example, the special argument name "
"``tmp_path`` is used in tests to create temporary directories. However, "
"fixtures should be used sparingly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:261
msgid "Parametric tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:263
msgid ""
"One very nice feature of ``pytest`` is the ease of testing across a range of "
"parameter values using the ``pytest.mark.parametrize`` decorator. For "
"example, suppose you wish to test ``linalg.solve`` for all combinations of "
"three array sizes and two data types::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:268
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.parametrize('dimensionality', [3, 10, 25])\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize('dtype', [np.float32, np.float64])\n"
"def test_solve(dimensionality, dtype):\n"
"    np.random.seed(842523)\n"
"    A = np.random.random(size=(dimensionality, dimensionality))."
"astype(dtype)\n"
"    b = np.random.random(size=dimensionality).astype(dtype)\n"
"    x = np.linalg.solve(A, b)\n"
"    eps = np.finfo(dtype).eps\n"
"    assert_allclose(A @ x, b, rtol=eps*1e2, atol=0)\n"
"    assert x.dtype == np.dtype(dtype)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:280
msgid "Doctests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:282
msgid ""
"Doctests are a convenient way of documenting the behavior of a function and "
"allowing that behavior to be tested at the same time.  The output of an "
"interactive Python session can be included in the docstring of a function, "
"and the test framework can run the example and compare the actual output to "
"the expected output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:288
msgid ""
"The doctests can be run by adding the ``doctests`` argument to the "
"``test()`` call; for example, to run all tests (including doctests) for "
"numpy.lib::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:292
msgid ""
">>> import numpy as np\n"
">>> np.lib.test(doctests=True)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:295
msgid ""
"The doctests are run as if they are in a fresh Python instance which has "
"executed ``import numpy as np``. Tests that are part of a NumPy subpackage "
"will have that subpackage already imported. E.g. for a test in ``numpy/"
"linalg/tests/``, the namespace will be created such that ``from numpy import "
"linalg`` has already executed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:303
msgid "``tests/``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:305
msgid ""
"Rather than keeping the code and the tests in the same directory, we put all "
"the tests for a given subpackage in a ``tests/`` subdirectory. For our "
"example, if it doesn't already exist you will need to create a ``tests/`` "
"directory in ``numpy/xxx/``. So the path for ``test_yyy.py`` is ``numpy/xxx/"
"tests/test_yyy.py``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:311
msgid ""
"Once the ``numpy/xxx/tests/test_yyy.py`` is written, its possible to run the "
"tests by going to the ``tests/`` directory and typing::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:314
msgid "python test_yyy.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:316
msgid ""
"Or if you add ``numpy/xxx/tests/`` to the Python path, you could run the "
"tests interactively in the interpreter like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:319
msgid ""
">>> import test_yyy\n"
">>> test_yyy.test()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:323
msgid "``__init__.py`` and ``setup.py``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:325
msgid ""
"Usually, however, adding the ``tests/`` directory to the python path isn't "
"desirable. Instead it would better to invoke the test straight from the "
"module ``xxx``. To this end, simply place the following lines at the end of "
"your package's ``__init__.py`` file::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:330
msgid ""
"...\n"
"def test(level=1, verbosity=1):\n"
"    from numpy.testing import Tester\n"
"    return Tester().test(level, verbosity)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:335
msgid ""
"You will also need to add the tests directory in the configuration section "
"of your setup.py::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:338
msgid ""
"...\n"
"def configuration(parent_package='', top_path=None):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    config.add_subpackage('tests')\n"
"    return config\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:345
msgid "Now you can do the following to test your module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:347
msgid ""
">>> import numpy\n"
">>> numpy.xxx.test()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:350
msgid ""
"Also, when invoking the entire NumPy test suite, your tests will be found "
"and run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:353
msgid ""
">>> import numpy\n"
">>> numpy.test()\n"
"# your tests are included and run automatically!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:358
msgid "Tips & Tricks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:361
msgid "Known failures & skipping tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:363
msgid ""
"Sometimes you might want to skip a test or mark it as a known failure, such "
"as when the test suite is being written before the code it's meant to test, "
"or if a test only fails on a particular architecture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:367
msgid "To skip a test, simply use ``skipif``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:369
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.skipif(SkipMyTest, reason=\"Skipping this test because...\")\n"
"def test_something(foo):\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:375
msgid ""
"The test is marked as skipped if ``SkipMyTest`` evaluates to nonzero, and "
"the message in verbose test output is the second argument given to "
"``skipif``.  Similarly, a test can be marked as a known failure by using "
"``xfail``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:380
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.xfail(MyTestFails, reason=\"This test is known to fail "
"because...\")\n"
"def test_something_else(foo):\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:386
msgid ""
"Of course, a test can be unconditionally skipped or marked as a known "
"failure by using ``skip`` or ``xfail`` without argument, respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:389
msgid ""
"A total of the number of skipped and known failing tests is displayed at the "
"end of the test run.  Skipped tests are marked as ``'S'`` in the test "
"results (or ``'SKIPPED'`` for ``verbose > 1``), and known failing tests are "
"marked as ``'x'`` (or ``'XFAIL'`` if ``verbose > 1``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:396
msgid "Tests on random data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:398
msgid ""
"Tests on random data are good, but since test failures are meant to expose "
"new bugs or regressions, a test that passes most of the time but fails "
"occasionally with no code changes is not helpful. Make the random data "
"deterministic by setting the random number seed before generating it. Use "
"``rng = numpy.random.RandomState(some_number)`` to set a seed on a local "
"instance of `numpy.random.RandomState`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:405
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can use `Hypothesis`_ to generate arbitrary data. "
"Hypothesis manages both Python's and Numpy's random seeds for you, and "
"provides a very concise and powerful way to describe data (including "
"``hypothesis.extra.numpy``, e.g. for a set of mutually-broadcastable shapes)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:410
msgid ""
"The advantages over random generation include tools to replay and share "
"failures without requiring a fixed seed, reporting *minimal* examples for "
"each failure, and better-than-naive-random techniques for triggering bugs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:415
msgid "Writing thread-safe tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:417
msgid ""
"Writing thread-safe tests may require some trial-and-error. Generally you "
"should follow the guidelines stated so far, especially when it comes to "
"`setup methods <#setup-and-teardown-methods>`_ and `seeding random data "
"<#tests-on-random-data>`_. Explicit setup and the usage of local RNG are "
"thread-safe practices. Here are tips for some other common problems you may "
"run into."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:423
msgid ""
"Using ``pytest.mark.parametrize`` may occasionally cause thread-safety "
"issues. To fix this, you can use ``copy()``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:426
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.parametrize('dimensionality', [3, 10, 25])\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize('dtype', [np.float32, np.float64])\n"
"def test_solve(dimensionality, dtype):\n"
"    dimen = dimensionality.copy()\n"
"    d = dtype.copy()\n"
"    # use these copied variables instead\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:434
msgid ""
"If you are testing something that is inherently thread-unsafe, you can label "
"your test with ``pytest.mark.thread_unsafe`` so that it will run under a "
"single thread and not cause test failures::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:438
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.thread_unsafe(reason=\"reason this test is thread-unsafe\")\n"
"def test_thread_unsafe():\n"
"  ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:442
msgid "Some examples of what should be labeled as thread-unsafe:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:444
msgid "Usage of ``sys.stdout`` and ``sys.stderr``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:445
msgid ""
"Mutation of global data, like docstrings, modules, garbage collectors, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:446
msgid "Tests that require a lot of memory, since they could cause crashes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:448
msgid ""
"Additionally, some ``pytest`` fixtures are thread-unsafe, such as "
"``monkeypatch`` and ``capsys``. However, ``pytest-run-parallel`` will "
"automatically mark these as thread-unsafe if you decide to use them. Some "
"fixtures have been patched to be thread-safe, like ``tmp_path``."
msgstr ""

